'''''Beaulieu v Finglam'''''<ref>[http://uulzii.com/search?q=Finglam&q1=beaulieu ''Finglam v Beaulieu''] 1401 B & M 557</ref> is a landmark and precedent setting case in [[English Law|English]] [[tort law]].<ref name="swarb1"/><ref>Ian Fitzharris [http://www.staredecisishibernia.com/owners-dwelling-liable-escape-fire-neighbours-property-arising-negligence-building-contractor/ Owners of dwelling liable for escape of fire to neighbour’s property arising from negligence of building contractor]</ref><ref>Courtney Stanhope Kenny, A Selection of Cases Illustrative of the English Law of Tort (Cambridge University Press, 2014) [https://books.google.com.au/books?id=zwlEBgAAQBAJ&pg=PA589&lpg=PA589&dq=Beaulieu+v+Finglam&source=bl&ots=NvhsDiQ3AM&sig=7r8raj42-OJQ5EG2DxB83a-5HFQ&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwimxNHS2oDWAhULJJQKHZMlCB0Q6AEISTAI#v=onepage&q=Beaulieu%20v%20Finglam&f=false p589]</ref> While specifically it set [[strict liability]] for the escape of fire, the judgment also demarcated the limits of [[Legal obligation|responsibility]] and [[Legal liability|liability]] for [[tort]] cases. It also established the first ''[[Ratio decidendi|ratio]]'' of what would become [[duty of care]].<ref>Sir John Baker, Baker and Milsom Sources of English Legal History:Private Law to 1750 (Oxford University Press, 2nd ed, 2010) 610.</ref><ref name="snayth">[[Stapleton v Snayth]] (1354) YB Pas 19, 32b-33a.</ref> Though a [[duty of care]] with regard to water<ref name="snayth"/> and animals <ref>[[Beneyt v Brokkere]] (1358)</ref><ref>[[Mason v Keeling]] (1700) 1 Ld Raym 606; 91 ER 1305.</ref><ref>Malone WS. (1970). Ruminations on the Role of Fault in the History of the Common Law of Torts. Louisiana Law Review.</ref> had already been established.
==Judgment == {{quote|‘A man is held to answer for the act of his servant or of his guest ... for if my servant or my guest [accidentally ... burns all my house and the house of my neighbour also, in this case I shall answer to my neighbour for his damage ... But if a man from outside my house and against my will starts a fire .... whereby my house is burned and my neighbours’ houses are burned as well, for this I shall not be held bound to them; for this cannot be said to be done by wrong on my part, but is against my will.’|''Beaulieu v Finglam'': 1401 B & M 557<ref name="swarb1">[http://swarb.co.uk/beaulieu-v-finglam-1401/ ''Beaulieu v Finglam'': 1401 B & M 557]</ref>}}
