{{unreferenced|date=July 2016}}
{{Criminology and penology}}
'''Denunciation''' in the context of [[Sentence (law)|sentencing philosophy]] is the disapproval of an act by society that is expressed by the imposition of a sentence. This is one of the purposes of sentencing, as well as a possible justification for the imposition of a sentence.

Denunciation arguments can be used to justify more serious sentences than are required by the principles of [[Retributive justice|retribution]] and [[Deterrence (legal)|deterrence]].

Denunciation arguments can also be used to justify the existence of laws which are never enforced; they stand as statements of a society's values rather than working parts of a criminal justice system.

