The '''law in Africa''' is a diverse mix of [[common law]], [[customary law]], [[Civil law (legal system)|civil law]] and [[religious law]] systems. Africa is the second largest continent and has 56 countries contained in it.
==History== Modern Africa has been shaped primarily through different countries' inheritance of laws which existed in Europe through the nineteenth century. For instance, the primary sources of [[South Africa]] law were Roman-Dutch and English Common law, imports of Dutch settlements and British colonialism. Thus it is sometimes termed Anglo-Dutch law. Various lawmaking bodies have existed within South Africa over time. Yet in fact, some of the oldest legal systems began first in Africa. For instance, Ancient Egyptian law used a civil code, based on the concept of [[Ma'at]]. Tradition, rhetorical speech, social equality and impartiality were key principles.[http://www.cap-press.com/authors/217]<ref>Russ VerSteeg, ''Law in Ancient Egypt'' (2002) {{ISBN|0-89089-978-9}}</ref> Judges kept records, which was used as precedent, although the systems developed slowly.
A [[polycentric law|polycentric]] [[legal system]], called ''[[Xeer]]'' developed exclusively in the [[Horn of Africa]] more than a millennium ago and is still widely used by the [[Somali people]]. Under this system, [[Elder (administrative title)|elders]] serve as judges and help mediate cases using precedents.<ref name="LALL"> {{cite web |title = Elder Counsel |url = http://www.legalaffairs.org/printerfriendly.msp?id=891 |date = October 2005 |author = Louisa Lombard |publisher = Legal Affairs |accessdate = 2009-06-26 }}{{dead link|date=December 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }} </ref> Xeer is a good example of how [[customary law]] can work in lieu of [[Civil law (legal system)|civil law]], and is a good approximation of what is thought of as [[natural law]]. Several scholars have noted that even though Xeer may be centuries old, it has the potential to serve as the legal system of a modern, well functioning economy.<ref name="PLBS"> {{cite web |author=Peter Leeson |title=Better of Stateless |url=http://www.peterleeson.com/Better_Off_Stateless.pdf}} </ref> <ref name="RKBA">[http://rkba.org/libertarian/maccallum/MacCallum-Somalia98.html A Peaceful Ferment in Somalia]</ref> <ref name="FAGA"> {{cite web |title=Free the Somali People |url=http://freeafrica.org/Archives/commentary%20407/commentaries18.html |author=George Ayittey |publisher=Free Africa Foundation |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120309104336/http://freeafrica.org/Archives/commentary%20407/commentaries18.html |archivedate=2012-03-09 |df= }}</ref> The Xeer also shows how influential a system of laws can be with regard to the development of a culture. According to one report, the Somali nation did not begin with the common use of the [[Somali language]] by the Somali clans, but rather with the collective observance of Xeer. ==International law== *[[African Union]]
