'''''Stone v. Trump''''' (1:17-cv-02459-MJG) is a lawsuit filed on August 28, 2017 in the [[United States District Court for the District of Maryland]]. The lawsuit alleges that President [[Donald Trump]]'s ban on [[transgender]] personnel joining the U.S. military violates their [[Equal Protection Clause|equal protection]] and [[Due Process Clause|due process]] rights. The [[American Civil Liberties Union]] (ACLU) of [[Maryland]] filed the suit on behalf of [[Petty Officer First Class]] Brock Stone, an 11-year veteran of the [[U.S. Navy]], and several other transgender service members.<ref name="sfgate-28aug2017">{{cite news|title=ACLU sues Trump over transgender military ban|url=http://www.sfgate.com/news/us/article/ACLU-sues-Trump-over-transgender-military-ban-12045392.php|accessdate=August 28, 2017|agency=[[Associated Press]]|newspaper=[[San Francisco Chronicle]]|date=August 28, 2017|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170829021920/http://www.sfgate.com/news/us/article/ACLU-sues-Trump-over-transgender-military-ban-12045392.php|archivedate=August 29, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref name="latimes-28aug2017">{{cite news|title=ACLU sues Trump over transgender military ban|url=http://www.latimes.com/politics/washington/la-na-essential-washington-updates-aclu-sues-trump-over-transgender-1503932393-htmlstory.html|accessdate=August 28, 2017|agency=Associated Press|newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]]|date=August 28, 2017}}</ref><ref name="npr-28aug2017">{{cite news|last1=Kennedy|first1=Merrit|title=2 Lawsuits Challenge Trump's Ban On Transgender Military Service|url=https://www.npr.org/sections/thetwo-way/2017/08/28/546731931/2-lawsuits-challenge-trumps-ban-on-transgender-military-service|accessdate=August 28, 2017|newspaper=[[NPR]]|date=August 28, 2017}}</ref><ref name="wapo-28aug2017">{{cite news|last1=Jouvenal|first1=Justin|title=ACLU challenges Trump administration’s transgender military ban|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/public-safety/aclu-challenges-trump-administrations-transgender-military-ban/2017/08/28/f3fb8ffc-8c09-11e7-8df5-c2e5cf46c1e2_story.html|accessdate=August 28, 2017|newspaper=[[The Washington Post]]|date=August 28, 2017}}</ref> In addition to President Trump, the suit names as defendants the Secretaries of [[United States Department of Defense|Defense]] ([[James Mattis]]), the [[United States Army|Army]] ([[Ryan McCarthy (U.S. Army)|Ryan McCarthy]], acting), the [[United States Navy|Navy]] ([[Richard V. Spencer|Richard Spencer]]), and the [[United States Air Force|Air Force]] ([[Heather Wilson]]).<ref name=17-cv-02459-doc1 />{{rp|1}}

==Background==
Trump first announced a policy banning transgender people from serving in the military in "any capacity" in a series of tweets on July 26, 2017, stating that allowing such service members would incur "tremendous medical costs and disruption". The decision reversed [[Obama administration]] policy to allow the enlistment of transgender personnel, which was initially approved by the [[United States Department of Defense|Department of Defense]] to begin July 1, but was delayed by Defense Secretary Mattis.<ref name="wapo-28aug2017" /><ref name="cnn-28aug2017">{{cite news|last1=de Vogue|first1=Ariane|title=Transgender service members sue over Trump military ban|url=http://www.cnn.com/2017/08/28/politics/transgender-service-members-military-ban/index.html|accessdate=August 28, 2017|newspaper=[[CNN]]|date=August 28, 2017}}</ref> Trump issued formal guidance on the ban to the Secretaries of Defense and [[United States Department of Homeland Security|Homeland Security]] in a memorandum on August 25, 2017.<ref name="wh-25aug2017">{{cite news|title=Presidential Memorandum for the Secretary of Defense and the Secretary of Homeland Security|url=https://www.whitehouse.gov/the-press-office/2017/08/25/presidential-memorandum-secretary-defense-and-secretary-homeland|accessdate=August 28, 2017|publisher=[[The White House]]|date=August 25, 2017}}</ref>

==History==
The initial complaint was filed on August 28, 2017 in the United States District Court for the District of Maryland on behalf of five named and one anonymous transgender personnel either currently serving on active duty or in the National Guard. The complaint cited news articles that "indicate that President Trump's motivations in abruptly announcing a transgender ban were largely political, reflecting a desire to placate legislators and advisers who bear animus and moral disapproval toward men and women who are transgender" and further stated there was "no evidence that this about-face in policy was supported by any study of the issue or any consultation with military officers, DoD [Department of Defense] officials, other military experts, or medical or legal experts".<ref name=17-cv-02459-doc1>{{cite web |url=https://www.aclu.org/legal-document/stone-v-trump-complaint |title=''Stone, et. al. v. Trump, et. al.'', Complaint for Declaratory and Injunctive Relief, Case 1:17-cv-02459-MJG |author= |date=28 August 2017 |publisher=American Civil Liberties Union |accessdate=2 November 2017}}</ref>{{rp|1,21}}

An amended complaint was filed on September 14, noting that one of the named plaintiffs, Staff Sergeant Kate Cole, had been denied medically-indicated surgery on September 8.<ref name=17-cv-02459-doc39>{{cite web |url=http://files.eqcf.org/wp-content/uploads/2017/09/39-Amended-Complaint.pdf |title=''Stone, et. al. v. Trump, et. al.'', First Amended Complaint for Declaratory and Injunctive Relief, Case 1:17-cv-02459-MJG |author= |date=14 September 2017 |publisher=Equality Case Files |accessdate=8 December 2017}}</ref>{{rp|7}} That same day, the Plaintiffs filed a motion for preliminary injunction. In the attached memorandum in support, the Plaintiffs noted that "President Trump’s asserted military justifications have already been studied at length and rejected ''by the military itself''. The Ban reflects a decision to single out a disfavored group and withdraw legal protection based not on evidence but animus, moral disapproval, and crass political calculation." The memorandum also argued that "each day that President Trump’s unconstitutional directive remains in effect, Plaintiffs and their families continue to grapple with the stress and uncertainty of having their careers, their livelihoods, and their medical care jeopardized by a Commander-in-Chief who rejects their service and their sacrifice."<ref name=17-cv-02459-doc40-2>{{cite web |url=http://files.eqcf.org/wp-content/uploads/2017/09/40-P-Mtn-PI.pdf |title=''Stone, et. al. v. Trump, et. al.'', Memorandum in Support of Plaintiffs' Motion for Preliminary Injunction, Case 1:17-cv-02459-MJG |author= |date=14 September 2017 |publisher=Equality Case Files |accessdate=8 December 2017}}</ref>{{rp|2}}

The [[United States Department of Justice Civil Division]] (USDOJ) filed a motion to dismiss on October 12, 2017, calling the request for a preliminary injunction "premature several times over" as Secretary Mattis's Interim Guidance of September 14, 2017 would prevent involuntary discharge, separation, or denied re-enlistment at least until March 2018.<ref name=17-cv-02459-doc52-1>{{cite web |url=https://www.aclu.org/legal-document/stone-v-trump-defendants-memo-support-motion-dismiss-and-opposition-preliminary |title=''Stone, et. al. v. Trump, et. al.'', Memorandum of Points and Authorities in Support of Defendants' Motion to Dismiss and in Opposition to Plaintiffs' Application for a Preliminary Injunction, Case 1:17-cv-02459-MJG |author= |date=12 October 2017 |publisher=American Civil Liberties Union |accessdate=2 November 2017}}</ref>{{rp|1}} Senior medical and commanding officers provided sworn statements that they would comply with the Interim Guidance, in support of USDOJ's arguments.<ref name=17-cv-02459-doc60>{{cite web |url=http://files.eqcf.org/wp-content/uploads/2017/11/60-Ds-Redacted-declaration-and-Interim-Guidance-iso-MTD-oppn-PI.pdf |title=''Stone, et. al. v. Trump, et. al.'', Defendants' Notice of Filing Redacted Declarations and the Interim Guidance, Case 1:17-cv-02459-MJG |author= |date=25 October 2017 |publisher=Equality Case Files |accessdate=8 December 2017}}</ref>

In response, the plaintiffs' attorneys filed an opposing motion on October 27, 2017 which noted the Presidential Memorandum of August 25, 2017 prohibited the accession (enlistment and commissioning) of transgender people into the military as of January 1, 2018, the funding of "sex-reassignment surgical procedures for military personnel" would cease on March 23, 2018, and the Secretary of Defense was directed to "return to the longstanding policy and practice on military service" which required involuntary discharge of personnel solely on the basis of their transgender status, also on March 23.<ref name=17-cv-02459-doc66>{{cite web |url=https://www.aclu.org/legal-document/stone-v-trump-defendants-memo-support-motion-dismiss-and-opposition-preliminary |title=''Stone, et. al. v. Trump, et. al.'', Plaintiff's Opposition to Defendants' Motion to Dismiss and Reply in Support of Motion for Preliminary Injunction, Case 1:17-cv-02459-MJG |author= |date=27 October 2017 |publisher=American Civil Liberties Union |accessdate=2 November 2017}}</ref>{{rp|1}} Three separate [[amicus curiae|''amici'' briefs]] were filed in support of the complaint, by [[The Trevor Project]] (October 26),<ref name=17-cv-02459-doc62>{{cite web |url=http://files.eqcf.org/wp-content/uploads/2017/11/62-Trevor-Project-Amicus-Brief-iso-PI.pdf |title=''Stone, et. al. v. Trump, et. al.'', Proposed Brief ''amicus curiae'' of the Trevor Project in Support of Plaintiffs' Motion for a Preliminary Injunction, Case 1:17-cv-02459-MJG |author= |date=26 October 2017 |publisher=Equality Case Files |accessdate=8 December 2017}}</ref> retired military officers (October 27/corrected October 30),<ref name=17-cv-02459-doc71>{{cite web |url=http://files.eqcf.org/wp-content/uploads/2017/11/71-Retired-Military-Officers-et-al-Amicus-Brief-iso-PI-oppn-MTD.pdf |title=''Stone, et. al. v. Trump, et. al.'', Corrected Brief of Retired Military Officers and Former National Security Officials as Amici Curiae in Support of Plaintiffs' Motion for a Preliminary Injunction and Opposition to Defendants' Motion to Dismiss, Case 1:17-cv-02459-MJG |author= |date=30 October 2017 |publisher=Equality Case Files |accessdate=8 December 2017}}</ref> and the same fourteen states and the District of Columbia which had collectively filed an earlier, similar brief in ''Doe v. Trump'' (October 30).<ref name=17-cv-02459-doc73>{{cite web |url=http://files.eqcf.org/wp-content/uploads/2017/11/73-States-Amicus-Brief-iso-PI.pdf |title=''Stone, et. al. v. Trump, et. al.'', Brief of ''Amici'' States Massachusetts, California, Connecticut, Delaware, Hawaii, Illinois, Iowa, Maryland, New Mexico, New York, Oregon, Pennsylvania, Rhode Island, Vermont, and the District of Columbia in Support of Plaintiffs' Motion for a Preliminary Injunction, Case 1:17-cv-02459-MJG |author= |date=30 October 2017 |publisher=Equality Case Files |accessdate=8 December 2017}}</ref> On November 3, the government filed a motion in support of their earlier motion to dismiss, stating the [[Presidential Memorandum for the Secretary of Defense and the Secretary of Homeland Security|Presidential Memorandum of August 25]] "specifically directs the Secretary of Defense to study how to address transgender individuals who are currently serving in the military and does not predetermine the outcome of that study" and the "reliance on statements that the President made on Twitter several weeks before issuing his Presidential Memorandum is misplaced."<ref name=17-cv-02459-doc77>{{cite web |url=https://www.aclu.org/legal-document/stone-v-trump-defendants-reply-support-motion-dismiss |title=''Stone, et. al. v. Trump, et. al.'', Defendants' Reply in Support of their Motion to Dismiss, Case 1:17-cv-02459-MJG |author= |date=3 November 2017 |publisher=American Civil Liberties Union |accessdate=14 November 2017}}</ref>{{rp|1,6}}

During this time, Judge Kollar-Kotelly issued a partial preliminary injunction to the proposed ban in ''Doe v. Trump'' on October 30. For ''Stone v. Trump'', the Plaintiffs filed a memorandum on October 31, asking to continue consideration of the preliminary injunction as several of the plaintiffs in this case were affected by the ban on medically necessary surgeries implemented by the Presidential Memorandum of August 25.<ref name=17-cv-02459-doc74>{{cite web |url=http://files.eqcf.org/wp-content/uploads/2017/11/74-P-Supp-Authority-iso-PI-oppn-MTD.pdf |title=''Stone, et. al. v. Trump, et. al.'', Notice of Supplemental Authority in Further Support Plaintiffs' Motion for a Preliminary Injunction and in Opposition to Defendants' Motion to Dismiss, Case 1:17-cv-02459-MJG |author= |date=31 October 2017 |publisher=Equality Case Files |accessdate=8 December 2017}}</ref> USDOJ argued on November 7 the preliminary injunction in ''Doe v. Trump'' "has, in large measure, provided Plaintiffs with the remedy that they seek at this stage" and "[t]his Court should therefore stay all proceedings".<ref name=17-cv-02459-doc78>{{cite web |url=http://files.eqcf.org/wp-content/uploads/2017/11/78-D-Response-Ps-Supp-Authority.pdf |title=''Stone, et. al. v. Trump, et. al.'', Defendants' Response to Plaintiffs' Notice of Supplemental Authority, Case 1:17-cv-02459-MJG |author= |date=7 November 2017 |publisher=Equality Case Files |accessdate=8 December 2017}}</ref>

===Preliminary injunction===
{{quote |text=President Trump’s tweets did not emerge from a policy review, nor did the Presidential Memorandum identify any policymaking process or evidence demonstrating that the revocation of transgender rights was necessary for any legitimate national interest. [...] Moreover, the Court finds that, based on the exhibits and declarations currently on the record, the Directives are unlikely to survive a rational review.  The lack of any justification for the abrupt policy change, combined with the discriminatory impact to a group of our military service members who have served our country capably and honorably, cannot possibly constitute a legitimate governmental interest. |author=Judge [[Marvin J. Garbis]] |source=''Stone v. Trump'', F.Supp.3d 747, 768<ref name="280-FSupp3d-768">{{cite court|litigants=Stone v. Trump|col=280|reporter=F.Supp.3d|opinion=747|pinpoint=768|court=D. Md.|date=2017|url=https://scholar.google.com/scholar_case?case=7245511831994563095|accessdate=26 November 2018}}</ref>}}

On November 21, 2017, Judge [[Marvin J. Garbis]] issued a preliminary injunction to the entire Presidential Memorandum of August 25.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/public-safety/a-second-judge-blocks-trump-administrations-proposed-transgender-military-ban/2017/11/21/d91f65e4-cee1-11e7-81bc-c55a220c8cbe_story.html |title=Federal judge says Trump administration can’t stop funding sex-reassignment surgery for military members |author=Marimow, Ann E. |date=21 November 2017 |newspaper=The Washington Post |accessdate=21 November 2017}}</ref> Judge Garbis's order also blocks the prohibition on gender reassignment surgery, going further than Judge [[Colleen Kollar-Kotelly|Kollar-Kotelly]]'s October 2017 injunction in the related case ''Doe v. Trump''.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/11/21/us/transgender-ban-military.html |title=Second Judge Blocks Trump's Transgender Ban in the Military |author=Philipps, Dave |date=21 November 2017 |newspaper=The New York Times |accessdate=22 November 2017}}</ref> In the order, Judge Garbis wrote "A capricious, arbitrary, and unqualified tweet of new policy does not trump the methodical and systematic review by military stakeholders qualified to understand the ramifications of policy changes", referring to the July tweets by President Trump announcing the reinstatement of the ban, which had caught Pentagon leadership by surprise and drew swift condemnation from senior retired officers.<ref name="280-FSupp3d-771">{{cite court|litigants=Stone v. Trump|col=280|reporter=F.Supp.3d|opinion=747|pinpoint=771|court=D. Md.|date=2017|url=https://scholar.google.com/scholar_case?case=7245511831994563095|accessdate=26 November 2018}}</ref>

===Appeals===
USDOJ filed a notice of appeal on December 5.<ref name=17-cv-02459-doc86>{{cite web |url=http://files.eqcf.org/wp-content/uploads/2017/12/86-Ds-Notice-of-Appeal.pdf |title=''Stone, et. al. v. Trump, et. al.'', Defendants' Notice of Appeal, Case 1:17-cv-02459-MJG |author= |date=5 December 2017 |publisher=Equality Case Files |accessdate=8 December 2017}}</ref> USDOJ also asked the Court to clarify on December 12 if Secretary Mattis retained independent authority to further delay the accession (the process of entering military service, whether through enlistment, Service Academy, ROTC, or similar programs) of transgender candidates.<ref name=17-cv-02459-doc91>{{cite web |url=http://files.eqcf.org/wp-content/uploads/2017/12/91-D-Mtn-Clarifiaction-and-Partial-Stay.pdf |title=''Stone, et. al. v. Trump, et. al.'', Defendants' Motion for Clarification and, if Necessary, a Partial Stay of Preliminary Injunction Pending Appeal, Case 1:17-cv-02459-MJG |author= |date=12 December 2017 |publisher=Equality Case Files |accessdate=18 December 2017}}</ref>{{rp|2}} Under the ''[[status quo]]'' enforced by the preliminary injunction, accession of transgender candidates was set to start on January 1, 2018. This date resulted from the postponement by Secretary Mattis of six months after the initial deadline of July 1, 2017 under the accession plan proposed by [[Ashton Carter|Secretary Carter]] in 2016. USDOJ asked for the clarification to be issued by noon, December 14.<ref name=17-cv-02459-doc91 />{{rp|9}}<ref name=17-cv-2398/>{{rp|1;6–7}} The parties had a conference on December 13, confirming that discovery should conclude by April 24, 2018, and the trial or hearing would be held in July 2018.<ref name=17-cv-02459-doc94>{{cite web |url=http://files.eqcf.org/wp-content/uploads/2017/12/94-Order-Confirming-Conference.pdf |title=''Stone, et. al. v. Trump, et. al.'', Order Confirming Conference, Case 1:17-cv-02459-MJG |author= |date=13 December 2017 |publisher=Equality Case Files |accessdate=18 December 2017}}</ref>

On December 14, USDOJ filed an emergency motion for a stay on Judge Garbis's order with the [[United States Court of Appeals for the Fourth Circuit|Fourth Circuit]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.washingtonblade.com/2017/12/14/trump-administration-not-done-fight-trans-military-enlistments/ |title=Trump admin not done fighting transgender military enlistments |author=Johnson, Chris |date=14 December 2017 |newspaper=Washington Blade |accessdate=15 December 2017}}</ref> The emergency motion used similar language to the emergency motion filed on December 11 with the [[United States Court of Appeals for the District of Columbia|D.C. Circuit]] in ''Doe v. Trump''.<ref name=17-cv-5267-doc1708433>{{cite web |url=https://thinkprogress.org/wp-content/uploads/2017/12/trump-trans-military-dc-appeal.pdf |title=''Jane Doe, et. al. v. Donald J. Trump, et. al.''; Appellants' Emergency Motion for Administrative Stay and Partial Stay Pending Appeal, Case 17-cv-05267 |author= |date=11 December 2017 |publisher=Think Progress |accessdate=12 December 2017}}</ref> Both appeal court motions asked for a stay that would allow Secretary Mattis to issue a second delay for accession of transgender candidates to military service. Alternatively, the stay could act to narrowly constrain the preliminary injunction to allow the accession of only Seven Ero George, the single Plaintiff in ''Stone v. Trump'' that Judge Garbis ruled had standing to challenge the ban on accessions.<ref name=17-cv-2398>{{cite web |url=http://www.washingtonblade.com/content/files/2017/12/Stone-CA4-Stay-Motion-FINAL-1.pdf |title=''Stone, et. al. v. Trump, et. al.'', Appellants' Emergency Motion for Administrative Stay and Partial Stay Pending Appeal, Case 17-cv-2398 |author= |date=14 December 2017 |publisher=Washington Blade |accessdate=15 December 2017}}</ref>{{rp|2–3}} Plaintiffs filed their opposition to the emergency motion on December 18, stating "[i]t was the President's unconstitutional actions that ended an orderly process [of planned accession]" and "[defendants did] not explain why the months of training that have already occurred are insufficient, or offer an explanation of what training they believe remains necessary and how long it would take."<ref name=17-cv-2398-doc17-1>{{cite web |url=https://www.aclu.org/legal-document/stone-v-trump-opposition-emergency-stay |title=''Stone, et. al. v. Trump, et. al.'', Opposition to Appellants' Emergency Motion for Administrative Stay and Partial Stay Pending Appeal, Case 17-cv-2398 |author= |date=18 December 2017 |publisher=ACLU |accessdate=22 December 2017}}</ref>{{rp|3,4}} In support, USDOJ stated "that implementation [of accession] was put on hold on August 25, 2017" and "the military will still have to take significant steps in order to meet an unexpected January 1 deadline".<ref name=17-cv-2398-doc20>{{cite web |url=https://www.aclu.org/legal-document/stone-v-trump-reply-support-emergency-stay |title=''Stone, et. al. v. Trump, et. al.'', Appellants' Reply in Support of Emergency Motion for Administrative Stay and Partial Stay Pending Appeal, Case 17-cv-2398 |author= |date=19 December 2017 |publisher=ACLU |accessdate=22 December 2017}}</ref>{{rp|8}}

Plaintiffs followed up with a memorandum of supplemental authority on December 19 after the Pentagon memorandum of December 8 outlining guidance for accession of transgender candidates was introduced in ''Karnoski v. Trump''.<ref name=17-cv-2398-doc23-1>{{cite web |url=https://www.aclu.org/legal-document/stone-v-trump-supplemental-authority-department-defense-memo |title=''Stone, et. al. v. Trump, et. al.'', Memorandum of Supplemental Authority, Case 17-cv-2398 |author= |date=19 December 2017 |publisher=ACLU |accessdate=22 December 2017}}</ref> USDOJ argued "Secretary Mattis cannot, without risking contempt, exercise his independent authority to give the military more time to consider a momentous change to its accession standards" and produced a follow-up memorandum, dated December 19.<ref name=17-cv-2398-doc24>{{cite web |url=https://www.aclu.org/legal-document/stone-v-trump-response-supplemental-authority |title=''Stone, et. al. v. Trump, et. al.'', Response to Memorandum of Supplemental Authority, Case 17-cv-2398 |author= |date=20 December 2017 |publisher=ACLU |accessdate=22 December 2017}}</ref>

On December 21, 2017, a panel of three judges on the Fourth Circuit denied USDOJ's emergency motion for a stay on Judge Garbis's order.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-usa-court-transgender/u-s-court-rejects-trump-bid-to-stop-transgender-military-recruits-on-jan-1-idUSKBN1EF2PP |title=US Court Rejects Trump Bid to Stop Transgender Military Recruits on Jan. 1 |author=Chung, Andrew |agency=Reuters |date=22 December 2017 |publisher=Reuters |accessdate=22 December 2017}}</ref><ref name=17-cv-2398-doc31>{{cite web |url=https://www.aclu.org/legal-document/stone-v-trump-order-denying-stay |title=''Stone, et. al. v. Trump, et. al.'', Order, Case 17-cv-2398 |author= |date=21 December 2017 |publisher=ACLU |accessdate=22 December 2017}}</ref> Judge Garbis also denied the Motion for Clarification and Partial Stay on December 28, noting the defendants were "request[ing] judicial advice as to what can be done to delay transgender accesstion to the military that will not risk a contempt finding" and they also had "not met their burden to establish irreparable harm if they must implement the accessions provision by January 1, 2018".<ref name=17-cv-02459-doc101>{{cite web |url=http://files.eqcf.org/wp-content/uploads/2018/01/101-Memo-and-Order-re-Clarification.pdf |title=''Stone, et. al. v. Trump, et. al.'', Memorandum & order re: Clarification, Case 1:17-cv-02459-MJG |author= |date=28 December 2017 |publisher=Equality Case Files |accessdate=29 January 2018}}</ref>{{rp|2}} USDOJ filed a motion to withdraw the appeal, which was granted on February 2, 2018.<ref name=17-cv-2398-doc38>{{cite web |url=http://files.eqcf.org/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/106-CA4-Order-granting-dismissal.pdf |title=''Stone, et. al. v. Trump, et. al.'', Order, Case 17-cv-2398 |author= |date=2 February 2018 |publisher=Equality Case Files |accessdate=3 April 2018}}</ref>

===Discovery===
On January 26, 2018, the Plaintiffs filed a motion to compel initial disclosures,<ref name=17-cv-02459-doc105>{{cite web |url=http://files.eqcf.org/wp-content/uploads/2018/01/105-Mtn-to-Compel-Initial-Disclosures.pdf |title=''Stone, et. al. v. Trump, et. al.'', Motion to Compel Initial Disclosures, Case 1:17-cv-02459-MJG |author= |date=26 January 2018 |publisher=Equality Case Files |accessdate=3 April 2018}}</ref> which was granted on February 6.<ref name=17-cv-02459-doc107>{{cite web |url=http://files.eqcf.org/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/107-Order-re-initial-disclosures.pdf |title=''Stone, et. al. v. Trump, et. al.'', Order re: Rule 26(a) Compliance, Case 1:17-cv-02459-MJG |author= |date=6 February 2018 |publisher=Equality Case Files |accessdate=3 April 2018}}</ref> In their motion, the Plaintiffs stated the "Defendants’ two-sentence “initial disclosure” contains none of the required identifications, and is tantamount to no disclosure at all" instead of identifying the individuals, documents, and information that may be used to support their defense.<ref name=17-cv-02459-doc105-1>{{cite web |url=http://files.eqcf.org/wp-content/uploads/2018/01/105-Mtn-to-Compel-Initial-Disclosures.pdf |title=''Stone, et. al. v. Trump, et. al.'', Memorandum in Support of Plaintiffs' Motion to Compel Initial Disclosures, Case 1:17-cv-02459-MJG |author= |date=26 January 2018 |publisher=Equality Case Files |accessdate=3 April 2018}}</ref> Both sides entered into an agreement to enable confidential documents to be designated as privileged and protected from public disclosure on February 12.<ref name=17-cv-02459-doc110>{{cite web |url=http://files.eqcf.org/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/110-Protective-Order-Inadvertant-Disclosure.pdf |title=''Stone, et. al. v. Trump, et. al.'', Federal Rule of Evidence 502(d) Order, Case 1:17-cv-02459-MJG |author= |date=12 February 2018 |publisher=Equality Case Files |accessdate=3 April 2018}}</ref><ref name=17-cv-02459-doc111>{{cite web |url=http://files.eqcf.org/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/111-Protective-Order.pdf |title=''Stone, et. al. v. Trump, et. al.'', Uniform Protective Order and Cross-Use Agreement, Case 1:17-cv-02459-MJG |author= |date=6 February 2018 |publisher=Equality Case Files |accessdate=3 April 2018}}</ref>

As in ''Doe v. Trump'', USDOJ moved to dismiss the claims against the President and partially dissolve the preliminary injunction on March 1, 2018, arguing "the President is not a proper defendant in this case" as [[Separation of powers under the United States Constitution|separation of powers]] dictates "the non-ministerial conduct of the President when he acts in his official capacity cannot be enjoined."<ref name=17-cv-02459-doc115>{{cite web |url=http://files.eqcf.org/wp-content/uploads/2018/03/115-D-Part-JOTP-and-Mtn-to-Dissolve-PI-in-part-.pdf |title=''Stone, et. al. v. Trump, et. al.'', Defendants' Partial Motion for Judgment on the Pleadings and Motion to Partially Dissolve the Preliminary Injunction, Case 1:17-cv-02459-MJG |author= |date=1 March 2018 |publisher=Equality Case Files |accessdate=3 April 2018}}</ref>{{rp|1;3}} In their response, counsel for the Plaintiffs characterized the motion as a "startling proposition [that] should be rejected" and the "President is no king, but he too may be sued. This court has the power to determine whether the President has acted within the law, and to declare that the President violated the law." They added the "Defendants’ argument that the President has absolute immunity from a lawsuit challenging
his own unconstitutional actions is based on little more than sleight-of-hand", noting the USDOJ arguments relied on citing cases where [[Injunction|injunctive relief]] was applied, instead of [[Declaratory judgment|declaratory relief]].<ref name=17-cv-02459-doc117>{{cite web |url=http://files.eqcf.org/wp-content/uploads/2018/03/117-P-Oppn-D-Part-JOTP-and-Mtn-to-Dissolve-PI-in-part-.pdf |title=''Stone, et. al. v. Trump, et. al.'', Memorandum in Opposition to Defendants' Partial Motion for Judgment on the Pleadings, and Response to Defendants' Motion to Partially Dissolve the Preliminary Injunction, Case 1:17-cv-02459-MJG |author= |date=9 March 2018 |publisher=Equality Case Files |accessdate=3 April 2018}}</ref>{{rp|1–2;4}} USDOJ replied that declaratory and injunctive relief were equivalent.<ref name=17-cv-02459-doc118>{{cite web |url=http://files.eqcf.org/wp-content/uploads/2018/03/118-D-Reply-iso-Part-JOTP-and-Mtn-to-Dissolve-PI-in-part-.pdf |title=''Stone, et. al. v. Trump, et. al.'', Defendants' Reply in Support of Their Partial Motion for Judgment on the Pleadings Motion to Partially Dissolve the Preliminary Injunction, Case 1:17-cv-02459-MJG |author= |date=16 March 2018 |publisher=Equality Case Files |accessdate=3 April 2018}}</ref>{{rp|2}}

===New Trump memorandum===
After President Trump issued [[Presidential Memorandum for the Secretary of Defense and the Secretary of Homeland Security Regarding Military Service by Transgender Individuals by Donald Trump (March 23, 2018)|a new memorandum on March 23, 2018]], revoking the prior Memorandum of August 25,<ref name=17-cv-02459-doc119>{{cite web |url=http://files.eqcf.org/wp-content/uploads/2018/03/119-D-Notice-New-Policy.pdf |title=''Stone, et. al. v. Trump, et. al.'', Defendants' Notice, Case 1:17-cv-02459-MJG |author= |date=23 March 2018 |publisher=Equality Case Files |accessdate=3 April 2018}}</ref> USDOJ moved to dissolve the preliminary injunction<ref name=17-cv-02459-doc120>{{cite web |url=http://files.eqcf.org/wp-content/uploads/2018/03/120-D-Mtn-to-Dissolve-PI.pdf |title=''Stone, et. al. v. Trump, et. al.'', Defendants' Motion to Dissolve the Preliminary Injunction, Case 1:17-cv-02459-MJG |author= |date=23 March 2018 |publisher=Equality Case Files |accessdate=3 April 2018}}</ref> and asked for a protective order.<ref name=17-cv-02459-doc121>{{cite web |url=http://files.eqcf.org/wp-content/uploads/2018/03/121-D-Mtn-for-Protective-Order.pdf |title=''Stone, et. al. v. Trump, et. al.'', Defendants' Motion for a Protective Order, Case 1:17-cv-02459-MJG |author= |date=23 March 2018 |publisher=Equality Case Files |accessdate=3 April 2018}}</ref> The motion to dissolve the preliminary injunction noted the new policy was not "a categorical ban based on transgender status, [but instead] this new policy, like the Carter policy before it, would turn on the medical condition of gender dysphoria and contain a nuanced set of exceptions allowing some transgender individuals, including every individual Plaintiff here, to serve."<ref name=17-cv-02459-doc120 />{{rp|1}} Since the new policy of March 2018 establishes gender dysphoria as a disqualifying medical condition,<ref name=17-cv-02459-doc120 />{{rp|6–8}} USDOJ argued "the military's new policy is constitutional", especially since the basis for the new policy asserted "that retaining the Carter policy would pose risks to military readiness".<ref name=17-cv-02459-doc120 />{{rp|2}} The proposed protective order asked that discovery should be halted, or the scope of discovery should be "significantly narrow[ed]" in light of the new policy.<ref name=17-cv-02459-doc121 />{{rp|1}}

On April 23, 2018, the Plaintiffs filed an amended complaint addressing the new Memorandum.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.aclu.org/legal-document/stone-v-trump-second-amended-complaint|title=''Stone, et. al. v. Trump, et. al.'', Second Amended Complaint for Declaratory and Injunctive Relief, Case 17-cv-02459|date=23 April 2018|publisher=[[ACLU]]|accessdate=26 November 2018}}</ref> The defendants filed a new motion to dismiss the amended complaint on May 11, arguing that the [[Department of Defense]] issued the new policy only after a "methodical and systematic review by military stakeholders qualified to understand the ramifications of policy changes."<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.aclu.org/legal-document/stone-v-trump-motion-dismiss-second-amended-complaint-or-motion-summary-judgment|title=''Stone, et. al. v. Trump, et. al.'', Defendants' Motion to Dismiss Plaintiffs' Second Amended Complaint, or, in the Alternative, Defendants' Motion for Summary Judgment, Case 17-cv-02459|date=11 May 2018|publisher=[[ACLU]]|accessdate=26 November 2018}}</ref>{{rp|49}}

On August 14, the court denied the defendants' motion for a protective order, and simultaneously granted the Plaintiffs' motion to compel the defendants to disclose documents in response to discovery.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://scholar.google.com/scholar_case?case=12547619241622805616&hl=en&as_sdt=6&as_vis=1&oi=scholarr|title=''Stone v. Trump'', Civil No. GLR-17-2459|date=14 August 2018|accessdate=26 November 2018}}</ref>

